"Pinto Jr. O., Pinto I.R.C.A.","On the sensitivity of cloud-to-ground lightning activity to surface air temperature changes at different timescales in São Paulo, Brazil",2008,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","113","20", D20123,"","",,,10.1029/2008JD009841,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58149252064&partnerID=40&md5=c504577a93153a2479b267b3e869db27","Brazilian Institute of Space Research, P.O. Box 515, São José dos Campos 12227-010, Brazil","Pinto Jr., O., Brazilian Institute of Space Research, P.O. Box 515, São José dos Campos 12227-010, Brazil; Pinto, I.R.C.A., Brazilian Institute of Space Research, P.O. Box 515, São José dos Campos 12227-010, Brazil","This paper presents a study about the sensitivity of cloud-to-ground (CG) lightning activity to changes in surface air temperature at daily, monthly, yearly, and decadal timescales in the city of São Paulo (Brazil). Lightning data collected in the city by the Brazilian Lightning Detection Network (BrasilDat) from 1999 to 2006 and thunderstorm day data obtained ftom 1951 to 2006 were analyzed and compared with surface air temperature data. The lightning activity increases significantly with increasing temperature, with a sensitivity of approximately 40% per 1°C for daily and monthly timescales and approximately 30% per 1°C for decadal timescale. For the yearly timescale, the increase is not statistically significant. The lower sensitivity for the decadal timescale suggests that the lightning sensitivity to changes in surface air temperature decreases for larger timescales, in agreement with what is expected on the basis of convective adjustment. The decadal lightning sensitivity found in this study is in reasonable agreement with the increase in the global lightning activity estimated by most climate models. The study is the first to investigate in detail this relationship in a large urban area inside the tropics and should contribute to the effort to understand the impact of the global warming on lightning activity. Copyright 2008 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Clouds; Lightning; Sensitivity analysis; Statistical methods; Thunderstorms; air temperature; climate modeling; cloud to ground lightning; convective system; decadal variation; global warming; sensitivity analysis; thunderstorm; urban area; Brazil; Sao Paulo [Brazil]; South America",,,,,,"Cabral, E., Funari, F.L., Comparative analysis of climatological data at the surface meteorological stations in the city of São Paulo: Agua Funda e Mirante de Santana (1997) Bol. Climatol. FCT/UNESP Presidente Prudente SP, 2 (3), pp. 218-222. , in Portuguese; Changnon, J., Assessment of the quality of thunderstorm data at first-order stations (2001) J. Appl. Meteorol, 40, pp. 783-794. , doi:10.1175/1520-0450(2001)040<0783:AOTQOT>2.0.CO;2; Changnon Jr., S.A., Climatography of thunder events in the conterminous United States: I. Temporal aspects (1988) J. Clim, 1, pp. 389-398. , doi:10.1175/1520-0442(1988)001<0389:COTEIT>2.0.CO;2; Report on Air Quality in the State of São Paulo (2004) (in Portuguese) (2005), Companhia de Tecnologia de Saneamento Básico , report, São Paulo, BrazilCummins, K.L., Murphy, M.J., Bardo, E.A., Hiscox, W.L., Pyle, R.B., Pifer, A.E., A combined TOA/MDF technology upgrade of the U.S. National Lightning Detection Network (1998) J. Geophys. Res, 103 (D8), pp. 9035-9044. , doi:10.1029/99JD00153; Cummins, K. L., E. P. Krider, and M. D. Malone (1998b), The U. S. National Lightning Detection Network and applications of cloud-to-ground lightning data by electric power utilities, IEEE Trans. Electr. Compat., 40(4), 465-480, doi:10.1109/15.736207(2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Changes , Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Ma, M., Shanchang, T.A.O., Baoyou, Z.H.U., Weitao, L.U., Yongbo, T.A.N., Response of global lightning activity to air temperature variation (2005) Chin. Sci. Bull, 50, pp. 2640-2644. ,